{
  "doc_id": "24899",
  "text": "Subsistence strategies are associated with many fundamental characteristics of human societies, including demography, settlement patterns, social and political organization and religious beliefs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . For most of human history, our species exclusively foraged for food via hunting, gathering and/or fishing [CITATION_5] . The subsequent spread of food production as a primary mode of subsistence has been referred to as 'the most important process in Holocene human history' [CITATION_6] . However, subsistence focused on plant-based agriculture has not been universally adopted. Even recently, hundreds of societies have maintained foraging as their primary mode of subsistence [CITATION_7] . Although most extant human groups use multiple subsistence strategies, the dominant strategy within a group varies widely across the planet [CITATION_8] (figure 1, see Material and methods for calculations).",
